snippet.textDisplay: I have to say this is a sad tragedy. People do not realize that helicopters go down all the time. According to the news so far they are not sure it was the fog that did this. Also it may have been clear at the time they left and they got caught in the middle of the morning fog. That is  hilly countryside and the weather can be very unpredictable. Placing blame on the pilot is pretty shitty. I'm sure he wasn't one to take risks with his own life. He had over 20 years of flying experience and that in and of itself says a lot about the man behind the controls. People need to realize that anything mechanical can break at any given time and that it is always, always, always a possibility. So this should not be a blaming session, this happens to people regularly. It is the risk you take to accomodate your lifestyle. The more you get off the ground the more your odds of crashing are possible. Helicopters are much more dangerous then planes. So, the odds go up. Yes it's devastating and yes it's sad. It is also sad for those in the military and those first responders in life flight saving lives yet risking theirs. If anyone is at fault it is our own government for not putting tougher regulations on heli flights and their safety systems! RIP to all those lost in this tragic accident. Sorry for your loss to the families, friends, coworkers, and also the pilot's family. Sadly you will all be missed and God Bless All!
